he ontology of Japan's linguistic make-up. Ryukyuan linguistics needs to be established as an independent field of study with its own research agenda and objects. This handbook delineates that the UNESCO classification is now well established and adequate. Linguists working on the Ryukyuan languages are well advised to refute the ontological status of the Ryukyuan languages as dialects. The Ryukyuan languages constitute a branch of the Japonic language family, which consists of five unroofed Abstand (language by distance) languages.The Handbook of Ryukyuan Languages provides for the most appropriate and up-to-date answers pertaining to Ryukyuan language structures and use, and the ways in which these languages relate to Ryukyuan society and history. It comprises 33 chapters, written by the leading experts of Ryukyuan languages. Each chapter delineates the boundaries and the research history of the field it addresses, comprises the most important and representative information.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Nov 2019) 0aJapanese languagexDialectsxHistory. 0aRyukyuan languagevHandbooks, manuals, etc. 0aRyukyuan languagexDialects. 0aRyukyuan languagexGrammar, ComparativexJapanese. 0aRyukyuan languagexGrammar. 0aRyukyuan languagexTerms and phrases. 4aGrammar Writing. 4aHistorical Linguistics. 4aLanguage Endangerment. 4aLanguage Revival and Revitalization. 4aRyukyuan Languages. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh1 aHeinrich, Patrick, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMiyara, Shinsho, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aShimoji, Michinori , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is 